1. e4 {Lovro Glavina: "Hey Igor ! I am an active member of the comments-giving
feedback and showing interest in the courses even when you dont give any
offers, so maybe I could get some extra credit so that you analyze my game? :D
Cuz you know, you dont get a lot of comments and then you get a lot of them
when there's some offer like your analysis. I don't want to seem childish, but
it's dissapointing when you comment on a lot of games and then you don't get
any credit(the analysis of Smirnov) for it when some offer is created and when
then lots of people paste their games... Its not my game but one of my
friends', and we're having a discussion(he's a 1685 fide and his opponent is
2200). He says that he lost because he didnt know theory. He couldn't find a5
without theory instead of 9... Nd4. Also, he says that it was extremely
difficult to realize with calculation that 13..d5 instead of 13.. d6 was much
better. What I'm trying to tell to him, is that he still didn't manage to
understand some of your principles. What do you think?"} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 (4... Nf6 {This is the Scotch opening. Black has two major
moves here, Bc5 and Nf6. Almost all strong players play the move Bc5, exept
Kramnik who prefers Nf6. Nf6 is a more simple and solid line. I can suggest
this move because you can learn it more easy.}) 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2
O-O {This is a rare move, but once played by Anand.} (7... d6 {This is more
common because Black is ready to develop the light-squared Bishop.}) 8. Bg5 h6
9. Bh4 (9. h4 d6 10. f3 hxg5 11. hxg5 Ng4 12. fxg4 Qxg5 13. Qf3 Bxg4 14. Qg3
Ne5 15. Be2 f5 16. exf5 Qxf5 17. O-O-O Bxe2 18. Nxe2 Qf2 19. Qh2 Qxe2 20. Qh8+
Kf7 21. Rdf1+ Bf2 22. Qh7 Ke6 23. Kb1 Qg4 {0-1 Rublevsky,S (2649)-Anand,V 
(2781)/Bastia 2004}) 9... Nd4 (9... a5 {Indeed here is the critical position
for Black. He has a lot of interesting options but before start making
different decisions, let's understand the position. White is little better,
thanks to his space advantage and more active pieces. We are in the opening,
so Black needs to develop the rest of his army. In the light of that the move
Re8 and d6 comes into my mind first. The move a5 looks the most popular move
acording to the megadatabase, however it is not the most logical move. Black
cannot really attack to the Queenside. White can easily stop this attack with
the a4 move and after that Black cannot open lines there, because he doesn't
have pawn breaks.} 10. a4 Nd4 {Not forced, but attractive. But I am not sure
that other continuations are easier to play.} (10... Re8 11. O-O-O $13) 11. Qd3
Nxb3 12. cxb3 Re8 13. O-O-O d6 14. Qc2 $1 {White's intention is to play Bc4,
and create some potential blow with e5, because the Rook d1 is opposite to the
Queen.} Bd7 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Rhe1 Qe7 17. e5 dxe5 18. Rxe5 {White created
another pin and he is threatening Nd5. The center is opened and White pieces
extremely active! He manages to win the game afterwards.} Qf8 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20.
Re2 Qg7 21. Bxe6 Rxe6 22. Rxe6 fxe6 23. Rd3 Kh8 24. Rg3 Qh7 25. Qd2 Bc5 26. Ne4
Be7 27. Rh3 Kg7 28. Qd7 Kf7 29. Ng5+ fxg5 30. Rf3+ Kg8 31. Qxe6+ Kh8 32. Rf7
Bd6 33. Rxh7+ Kxh7 34. Qf7+ Kh8 35. g3 Ra6 36. Kb1 Bb4 37. f4 gxf4 38. gxf4 {
1-0 Carlsen,M (2826)-Bacrot,E (2716)/Nanjing 2010/CBM 139/[Edouard,R]}) (9...
d5 10. Nxd5 g5 11. O-O-O Nxd5 12. exd5) 10. Qd3 Nxb3 11. axb3 Re8 12. O-O-O c6
$2 {I can understand this move. He ties to prevent the Nd5 move. Strong
players try to avoid such ugly moves at any costs. The c6 is not helping the
development of the pieces and creates weakness on the "d6" square.} (12... d6
$1 13. Nd5 g5 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $17 {White realized his "threat" and now we can
see that Black brings the Queen to the defence. In the light of that his
Kingside is totally secure. I'm strongly recommend to study the video lessons
"break the stereotypes". You will learn a lot of things for the pin. ;-)}) 13.
f4 d6 14. Be2 g5 $2 {He cracked under the pressure. This is not a good move at
all. We should not open lines in the position where we are under attack. In a
chess game we are fighting to put our pieces in his maximum activity. The pin
is limited our pieces mobility. Thus, we need to unpin when we have the
oportunity. On the other hand, Black tried to use tactics, but tactics are
working good for the side which has a better and more active position. Thus,
after some forcing moves Black end up with a piece down and he lose the game.}
(14... Qe7 $1) 15. fxg5 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bf5 17. Nf6+ Qxf6 18. gxf6 Bxd3 19. Bxd3
1-0

