activate my rock. But Berlin defence type of play helped me to activate my
piece and king on the center."} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3
6. bxc3 c5 7. Be2 $6 {This is not a suitable move for Grunfeld. Thus the
problem is that you are not familiar with this system. I strongly recommend
you to study the course "mastering the Grunfeld as Black pieces". This is a
course on how to play as Black, but you can understand better the lines and
what are the Black's plans. Then you can play better as white as well!
Similarly, if you would like to understand better the situation then you need
to play some times this position with the Black pieces. The last move, Be2 is
not good. Perhaps White would like to prevent the pin on g4. If this is the
point then he should play Bc4 and Ne2! In this way he can avoid the pin with
the pawn push to f3.} (7. Bc4) 7... Bg7 8. Be3 Nc6 9. Bb5 (9. Nf3 $5 Bg4 10. e5
{White's position doesn't look great, however he continues developing his
pieces.}) 9... cxd4 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Bxd4 O-O $5 (11... e5 $5 12. Bc5 Ba6 $15
{Both sides prevented the castle, but Black has the Bishop pair. Thus he has a
small plus in the position.} 13. Qa4 $2 Bb5) 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Qd4+ (13. Qxd8
Rxd8 14. Nf3 Ba6 15. Nd4 c5 16. Nb3 {Perhaps the best move for White is to
accept the Queen exchange and fight in the endgame for equality. White's
position doesn't look great, but it is not losing yet.}) 13... Kg8 $6 (13...
Qxd4 $1 {Black is dreaming about the attack and for that reason he didn't
exchanged the Queens. However he is far ahead in the development so he should
created the weakness on d4 and start attacking it.} 14. cxd4 Rd8 15. Ne2 (15.
Nf3 Ba6) 15... Ba6 $17 {Black's position is close to winning, thanks to his
powerful Bishop on a6. White pieces are paralyzed and the Rook on h1 cannot
participate in the game.}) 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rd1 Ba6 16. Nf3 Rab8 17. Rxd8+
Rxd8 18. Nd4 {After some mutual mistakes we reached the same endgame which we
analyzed above. White is squeezed and the Bishop is stronger than the Knight
because the position is open and he can find better diagonals. In the other
hand, the Knight cannot find a good outpost. Black manages to excnage a pair
of Rooks and he can feel little more safer for that. However he needs to
activate the Rook from h1.} c5 19. Nc6 Rd7 20. h4 $5 h5 21. Rh3 Rb7 22. a4 $1 {
White is defending well. He saw Black's threat Rb1 and Rb2, so he protects the
"a" pawn.} f6 (22... Rb1+ 23. Kd2 Rb2+ (23... Ra1 24. Nxe7+) 24. Ke3 Re2+ 25.
Kf3 Kg7 26. Nxe7 Bd3 {This is the most precise continuation for Black, however
it is very difficult to find it during the game. With the series of checks
Black limited the activity of White's Rook on h3 and then he exchanged the "e"
pawns. Black will get back the pawn, but the position remains complicated.
White can defend himself.}) (22... Kf8 23. Rf3 Rb1+ 24. Kd2 Ra1 25. Ne5 $1) 23.
Rg3 $1 {It is amazing how the Rook from h1 enters the game creating threats.
The game is in tension and White is fighting back. He manages to create
problems and complicate the position. He is on the right track!} Kg7 (23... Kh7
$1) 24. f4 {Black, without any obvious reason, pin his own King and White
takes the advantage of it in order to create more problems.} Bc4 25. f5 Bf7 26.
Nd8 Rb1+ 27. Kd2 Ra1 28. Nxf7 Kxf7 29. Rxg6 Rxa4 {After this forcing line the
position is equal. This was a really cool defending game by White.} 30. Kd3 e6
31. Rh6 exf5 32. exf5 Rxh4 33. Rh7+ Kg8 34. Rxa7 {When we are defending we
should exchange more pawns, so White plays good!} Rf4 35. Rc7 Rxf5 36. Ke4 Rg5
37. Kf3 h4 38. Kf4 Rxg2 39. Rxc5 h3 40. Rh5 h2 41. c4 $1 {White pieces are
extremely active and he can create a good counterplay. He will manage to
