1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 {This is not the best variation for White.
White lost a lot of his opening potentials. The position is about equal,
however White cannot try to create any real problems to Black.} 4. Nf3 Bd6 5.
Nc3 Ne7 6. Bg5 f6 {It seems that this move weakness the e6 square but control
the imortant square e5. Black can control e6 with the light-square Bishop.
Similarly, later on on the game, Black can think about Kingside expansion with
g5 or to capture the bishop pair with Nf5 move.} 7. Bh4 Bf5 $5 (7... O-O) (7...
c6) 8. Bd3 O-O {Black uses tactics in order to protect the d5 pawn.} 9. Bg3 (9.
Bxf5 Nxf5 10. Nxd5 g5 $1 (10... Re8+ $5) 11. Bg3 Bxg3 12. hxg3 Qxd5 $19) 9...
c6 10. Qd2 Re8 11. O-O-O b5 (11... Na6 $6 12. Bxa6 bxa6 {Perhaps Black can
create some counter-play via the "b" line, however the doubled ''a" pawn will
be there forever. Thus, this is a very risky decision.}) 12. Bxf5 Nxf5 13. Qd3
Qd7 14. Rde1 Na6 {The idea is to play Nb4 and a5. Black cannot attack on the
Queenside, however he should prepare the attack there.} 15. a3 $6 {This is not
a good move because Black can prepare and open the lines with the b4 move in
the future.} (15. -- Nb4 16. Qd2 a5) 15... Nc7 16. Re2 Rxe2 (16... a5 17. Rhe1
Bxg3 18. hxg3 Nd6 {Black has a very aggressive position and potentials to
attack in the Queenside.}) 17. Nxe2 a5 18. Bxd6 Nxd6 19. b3 a4 $5 {It is
better to move forward the pieces and only then to move the pawns. Pawns
cannot go back. Ne4 is a tempo, so White should defend instantly the f2.} (
19... Ne4) 20. Kb2 axb3 21. cxb3 Ne4 22. Rf1 Qg4 $2 {This is a move without a
plan. Amateurs are generated only one thread per time. Strong players start
with a plan and then he is trying to follow it. Black started played in the
Queenside, so he should continue his attack there.} (22... Qd6 $1 23. b4 Ne8 $1
{Very cool maneuver. The Knight is striking to the weak c4 square. White
cannot do anything to avoid this maneuver.} 24. h3 Qc7 25. Nd2 Nxd2 26. Qxd2
Nd6 {The pawn on a3 is deadly weak. I hope you can understand it by now and
you will never move the pawns in front of your king again...}) 23. g3 c5 $2 {
This is a total violations of chess strategy! When you are planning you should
choose one area and attack there. You can attack on the center, Kingside or
Queenside. Black players is very optimistic and he things that he owns the
chessboard. Indeed, if we go back some moves, Black was better. It was little
better. Now the position is very complicated and White can generate the
counter-play.} (23... Qd7 24. -- Qe7) 24. dxc5 Nxc5 25. Qc3 N7e6 {Qe4 was the
best move, however it was very difficult for Black to find it. Black has lost
the control of the position. The position is complicated and Black is in
danger. Phycologicaly it is very hard to play here as Black. Some moves ago
you was in the top of the world and now White can generate the strong threats.}
(25... Qe4 26. -- (26. Qxc5 Qxe2+ 27. Kb1 Qxf1+ $19) 26... Nd3+) 26. Nfd4 b4 $2
{This is another consequence of the previous wrong plan. Black player still
believes that he is better in the position, so he tries to prove his advantage
by sacrificing material. White has the upper hand and he is threatening to
capture on e6 and Qc6. Thus, Black should defend it.} (26... Qh5 $5) (26... Re8
$5) 27. axb4 (27. Nxe6 Qxe2+) 27... Ne4 28. Qc6 Rd8 29. Qxe6+ Qxe6 30. Nxe6 {
Black won the game on time, however his position is totally lost.} 0-1

