this move. In the opening we should develop our pieces and by this last move
White is violating this strategic rule.} (8. d3) 8... Ba6 9. d3 c4 10. Ne4 $1 {
This is the best move in the position. White is puting pressure against the d6
pawn.} (10. d4 $5 {This is another intresting option. The idea is to play
against the Bishop a6.}) 10... d5 (10... Bf8 {This was almost forced. If your
opponent must do such a passive moves, this is a sign that you have a very
good position.}) 11. Nd6+ Ke7 12. Be3 {White have fantastic pieces. The Bishop
will go to c5 and it can generate very strong threats against the Black's
uncastle King.} Nh6 13. Bc5 Kd7 14. dxc4 Rb8 (14... Bxc4 15. Nxc4 {Black
cannot recapture.}) 15. b3 $18 {By this point White have material advantage,
so his position is winning.} Qa5 16. Qd4 Nf5 17. Nxf5 gxf5 18. Rfd1 Rhc8 19.
Ng5 {This move is OK but I'm guessing that White is playing without a plan and
he just move the pieces around. In order to have a succesfull attack we need
the Queen in the most active square. Thus, White best move is Bd6 in order to
threate a7 pawn with check. White have fantastic position, however he is not
winning yet. In such sitouations you need to play very acourately and you
should not think that your position will win by itself...} (19. Bd6) 19... f6
